 &gt; Correct me if I&#39;m wrong, but I get the impression that Quikscript has
&gt; developed standard Quikscript spellings based on American
&gt; pronunciations.
&gt; 
&gt; I speak British English, although I&#39;m perfectly comfortable hearing
&gt; American English. When it comes to spontaneously writing Quikscript,
&gt; however, I write the British way, and have had cause for pause while
&gt; reading examples of Quikscript spelt the American way. Of course, the
&gt; difficulty lasts just a moment, but the experience gave rise to the
&gt; reflection that one of the factors that makes English a worldwide
&gt; language is that the spelling (however atrociously complicated and
&gt; irregular) is understood all over the English-using world,

This strikes me as the same argument for the Chinese continuing to use
their form of writing because it enables Mandarin and Cantonese speakers
to read what the other has written even though their languages are
mutually unintelligible.  I would assume that most English speakers
would not want our method of writing to become more ideographic than it
currently is.

If, in fact, English is becoming a worldwide language, I believe it is
due primarily to political and economic factors.  I cannot take
seriously the idea that the consistent (and abominable) spelling of T.O.
has much effect on the spread of English.  If that were the case, what
would account for the decline of French as the language of diplomacy?
Is it not spelt the same all over the world?

I am a U.S. citizen.  I corresponded with a New Zealander in Quikscript
(this is Read&#39;s spelling, by the way, and recent posts by dshepx on the
Shavian site persist in spelling it incorrectly:  &quot;Quickscript&quot;) in the
mid-1970s.  I found it delightful that his accent came through in his
letters.  Yes, occasionally, I was a little slow in deciphering some
words, but it was never a problem which interfered with communication.

I would agree that consistent spelling would aid reading speed, but I
don&#39;t think it needs to be a &quot;cultural fetish&quot; as Mr. Read put it.  I do
not believe that the number of words that would be spelt dramatically
differently from one accent to another would pose an insurmountable
communication problem.   The idea that there is one and one only
&quot;correct&quot; spelling needs to be laid to rest.  I think the idea of
correct spelling came about through the hegemony of printers and because
of the difficulty of conformity with a T.O. standard for many people
because it is so &quot;atrociously complicated and irregular.&quot;  I believe it
is accurate to say that in the late sixteenth century few people
believed there was one &quot;right&quot; way to spell a word.  The purpose of
writing is communication, and if a reader can understand the words the
writer wrote, even if some of them are spelt differently than the reader
would have spelt them, then communication has taken place even if
sticklers for uniformity don&#39;t like it.

 (despite
&gt; discrepancies betwen Ameican and English spellings). Differences in
&gt; pronunciation don&#39;t come in the way. For example, while I find it hard
&gt; to understand Australian speech, I have no problems with Australian
&gt; English as expressed in newspapers or internet sites. 
&gt; 
&gt; I remember the story of the Australian who woke up in a hospital bed
&gt; and saw a friend in the next bed. He asked, &quot;Did you come here to
&gt; die?&quot; Replied his friend, &quot;Yes, to die!&quot; For any who have never heard
&gt; an Australian speaking, the dialogue went thus: &quot;Did you come here
&gt; today?&quot; &quot;Yesterday.&quot;
&gt; 
&gt; Imagine an Australian writing the words &quot;today&quot; and &quot;yesterday&quot; in
&gt; Quikscript the way he pronounces it! Neither the Englishman nor the
&gt; American would be likely to guess what it means.
&gt; 
&gt; What do you feel about standardizing Quikscript spellings to the sound
&gt; of British English? The argument in favor would be that it is
&gt; understood in all the former British colonies, probably including the
&gt; USA.

This is an amusing anecdote, but it does not reflect reality.  If an
American in the hospital ward could figure out what was being
communicated, then so could a reader.  For example, even if the words
sounded like &quot;yes, to die&quot; to the American, it would be written as one
word since &quot;yesterday&quot; is one word.  Surely, this would be contextual
clue to even the densest reader.

Paige Gabhart








